---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import DesignSim from "../../components/DesignSim.astro";
import Reveal from "../../components/Reveal.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "design-first")!;
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn Claude`}>
  <main>
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        <strong>Claude Design</strong> turns a sentence into a working piece of interface.
        Below is an imitation: prompt input on the left, a live preview on the right.
        Hit <strong>Generate</strong>, then try the variant chips ("Bakery hero",
        "Login form", "Pricing") and the style buttons (Warm / Dark / Brutalist).
      </p>

      <DesignSim />

      <h2>Things to notice</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Words shape the output.</strong> "Pricing" gets a three-tier table. "Login form" gets a centred login. "Bakery" gets a hero with imagery vibes.</li>
        <li><strong>Style words pull the design</strong> in a direction — "premium dark mode" lights up the Dark variant; "raw, brutalist" pulls the Brutalist variant.</li>
        <li><strong>You can iterate.</strong> Edit the prompt or pick a different style; press Generate again. The real product keeps a history of versions you can roll back to.</li>
        <li><strong>It exports.</strong> "Copy code" gives you the HTML — paste it into your project.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Writing a first prompt</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p style="margin-top: 0;"><strong>A simple template:</strong></p>
        <pre>A [type of screen] for [audience]. [Two or three style words]. Include [content].</pre>
        <p><strong>Worked example:</strong></p>
        <pre>A landing page for a sourdough bakery. Warm, hand-drawn, generous whitespace.
Hero with a loaf photo, a three-card menu section, an order form at the bottom.</pre>
      </div>

      <h2>Style words that work well</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Tone:</strong> playful, serious, premium, retro, brutalist, soft, technical, friendly.</li>
        <li><strong>Density:</strong> generous whitespace, compact, dashboard-dense.</li>
        <li><strong>Inspiration:</strong> "like Linear", "like a Japanese menu", "like an old paperback".</li>
      </ul>

      <Reveal q="Can it use my real brand colours?">
        Tell it. "Use #1F2937 for headings and #F97316 for accents." Or upload a brand guide and reference it.
      </Reveal>
    </LessonShell>
  </main>
</Layout>
